SIMPLE: sniff
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sniff
<hw>Sniff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sniffed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Snift</conjf>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Sniffing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>sneven</ets>; akin to <ets>snivel</ets>, <ets>snuff</ets>; cf. Dan.
<ets>snive</ets> to sniff. See <er>Snuff</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<def>To draw air audibly up the nose; to snuff; -- sometimes done as a
gesture of suspicion, offense, or contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So ye grow squeamish, gods, and <qex>sniff</qex> at heaven.</q>
<rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sniff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sniff
<hw>Sniff</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw in with the
breath through the nose; <as>as, to <ex>sniff</ex> the air of the
country</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To perceive as by sniffing; to snuff, to scent; to
smell; <as>as, to <ex>sniff</ex> danger</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sniff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sniff
<hw>Sniff</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of sniffing; perception by
sniffing; that which is taken by sniffing; <as>as, a <ex>sniff</ex> of
air</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sniffing</ent>⟦br⟧
